=========================================
update-item-status.php
=========================================

Catching the Data ($_POST): When you click the green "Approve" button on your table, 
the form packages up the item_id and the status (which you set to STATUS_APPROVED using your constants) 
and hurls it at this file. The $_POST array acts like a catcher's mitt to grab those specific pieces of data.

Safety First (isset and (int)): We never trust data coming from a browser. 
isset() just makes sure the data actually arrived before we try to use it 
(preventing ugly PHP warnings). Putting (int) in front of the ID forces it 
to be a whole number, which is a great defense against hackers trying to inject malicious SQL code.

The Audit Trail ($_SESSION['user_id']): Because Lady's database schema requires a 
processed_by ID, we grab the currently logged-in Admin's ID directly from the session. 
This leaves a permanent digital footprint of exactly who approved or rejected the item.

The Handoff (updateItemStatus): This is the magic moment where your module connects to 
Lady's. You feed her function the exact 5 ingredients it asked for.

The Redirect (header("Location: ...")): A backend processing script like this shouldn't 
display any HTML. Once it finishes its job, it uses the header() function to instantly 
teleport the admin back to the page they were just on, adding a tiny ?msg=success to the 
end of the URL so you can display a "Success!" popup later if you want.